Roman'; font-size:12pt">thoughts on three issues; first, the decision of the European</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Court of Human Rights in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> case which has given rise to the current situation; secon</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dly the response of successive </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overnments to the Court’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">decision; and thirdly the options set out in the draft Bill.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In writing I wish to stress that I do so in a wholly personal capacity. While I was the Chair of the Commission on a Bill of Rights which reported in December 2012, this response to the Committee’s call for evidence reflects purely my own</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> views, albeit influenced by the work which I undertook as the Commission’s Chair. Nor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, as a non-lawyer,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> do I make any pretence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">bas</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> these comments on a legal analysis of the European Court of Human Rights’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> judg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ment in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> case; rather they reflect simply my </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">own </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">views as an interested lay observer. That said, the continuing debates over the Court’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s judg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ment in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> were a constant backdrop to the work of the Commission which I chaired and I therefore welcome this opportunity to be able to express my own views on some of the issues involved.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The decision of the Euro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">pean Court of Human Rights in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">rst</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Having read much that has been wri</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tten on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by numerous commentators and heard at first hand some of the views expressed by notable legal and political commentators on the case my own view is that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">European </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Court </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of Human Rights </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overreached itself in its judg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ment on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I take this view based not on a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ny</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> legal analysis of the Court’s decision but on a far simpler and more basic view, namely that whether prisoners should or should not have a right to vote while serving their sentences seems to me </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not to be an issue of fundamental human rights bu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t rather to be a political judg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">best decided by elected polit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">icians rather than a legal judg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ment to be decided by judges, whether </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">national</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or international. Put another way </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is clearly a question on which wholly responsible and entirely reasonable people can and do take very different views. As such it see</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ms to me to be eminently a judg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ment which should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the political not the legal realm.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My view is reinforced by the fact that the European Convention on Human Rights is entirely silent on this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">specific </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">issue. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Court’s decision has thus been based on an interpretation of the Convention. While such interpretations are clearly a part of the Court’s remit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> my own view is that it should be wary of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">making such interpretations when in doing so it is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">venturing into territory</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which many would regard as essentially political rather than judicial. The risk of doing so, which has clearly occurred a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s a result of its decision in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, is that the Court itself becomes increasingly seen as a political rather than </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">judicial animal and is thus sucked into a spiral of allegations and counter-allegations about the behaviours and motivations of its judges and officials.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I think it a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">pity that the Court</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> having had opportunities through other cases </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to reconsider its decision on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has chosen not to do so; I th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ink if a further opportunity were</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to arise it would be an act of considerable maturity on its part to reconsider whether the issue of prisoner voting is in fact one which it as a court should decide.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The response of successive UK g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">overnments to the decision in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Hi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">rst</span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> All of which said, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fact is that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Court has made a decision in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> case with which successive </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">governments have, so far at least, failed to comply</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> over a period of more than 7 years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">That it seems to me is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">unfortunate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and reflects badly on both the present Government and its predecessor. It is in the nature of any legal system, and inherent in respect for the rule of law, that all courts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> whether they </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> national or international - will from time to time reach decisions which democratically elected governments do not welcome. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Tempting though it may be in such circumstances to resist implementing the decisions in question, to do so ultimately weakens respect for the rule of law which is undoubtedly one of the fundamental pillars on which any genuinely free society rests. To the extent that no further avenues of appeal against such a decision remain it is in my view the duty of the government of the day to comply with it.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It can, of course, be argued - and with some justification - that what distinguishes decisions of domestic courts in such circumstances from those of certain international courts such </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as the European Court of Human Rights</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is that in the former case it is open to the government to, in effect, reverse the court’s decision through the passage of legislation while that option </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may not be open to it in the case of the decision of an international court. That is true, and it is not a trivial point. But it is nevertheless the case that the country and Parliament concerned will in general have specifically decided to confer that authority on the court </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in question </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and it is clearly undesirable, having done so, not to be willing ultimately to accept the consequences in particular cases. To follow that view through from the general to the particular I think it is to the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> credit neither of the present G</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overnment nor of its predecessor that it has not implemented the Court’s judgment and I would express the hope that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">present G</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overnment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">might </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">now decide to do so.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The options set out in the draft Bill</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In fact the Government’s options, were it minded to follow this course, are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> reasonably open</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Perhaps as a recognition of the controversy which its decision in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has caused, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">European Court of Human Rights </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has made clear that the Government, while it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">can not</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> lawfully continue with a total ban on prisoner voting, has considerable flexibility to decide which serving prisoners should or should not have the right to vote. It is quite clear that the Court is not in any way requiring all prisoners to be given the vote.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It would, I think, be inconsistent with my view as expressed earlier in this note that decisions on prisoner voting should essentially </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ones </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that should be taken by elected</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> representatives for me to put forward a purely personal view as to which of the options in the draft Bill, or indeed any other options, should be adopted. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Rather I </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would say that the G</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overnment might want to seek a solution which stays as close to its preferred </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">policy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as possible while genuinely meeting the requirement to comply with the Court’s decision. That is obviously closer to option b. of the three options in the draft Bill than it is to either option a. or c. but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">does not mean that it is the only possible option which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Government </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">could properly adopt. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What matters more, in my view, is to end the present stand-off which has continued for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">far </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">too long to the benefit of neither </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the G</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overnment nor the Court. But while </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">if that were to occur </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">some in the Court might be tempted to see </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as a victory it will have come only at the cost of considerable damage to the Court’s standing and reputation in the eyes of many in the UK. That is hopefully something that the Court’s current President and judges will consider before lightly reaching another </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> type judgment. For with power must come responsibility; the risk otherwise is that the Court will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ultimately </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be infringing the democra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tic rights of Europe’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> citizens, not protecting them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">June 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>